<!--************************************************************
Author: University of Minnesota PreCalculus Dept.
Reviewed/Remixed by: Doenet team

About the problem: Given a recursivle formula for a sequence and a specified initial term, determine the kth term of the sequence. This problem has two versions:
Version 1: a simpler version where the sequence always has the form 2 a_(n-1) - 1. The value of the initial term and the required term vary
Version 2: the sequence formula varies, negative values allowed

Delete or comment out the <hint> to remove the Worked Example.

*************************************************************--> 
<problem><title/>
<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name="a" from="2" to="4"/>
  <selectFromSequence name="p" from="4" to="6"/>
  
  <math name="expr">2 a_(n-1) - 1</math>
  <math name="a_p">($a - 1)2^($p - 1) + 1</math>
  <!--discrete steps for solution section-->
  <math name="step1">2*$a - 1</math>
  <math name="step2">2 $step1{simplify} - 1</math>
  <math name="step3">2 $step2{simplify} - 1</math>
  <math name="step4">2 $step3{simplify} - 1</math>
  <math name="step5">2 $step4{simplify} - 1</math>
  <!--maths for incorrect responses-->

</setup>


<!--testing-->
